Commentary.Commentary: We are back for India's first innings! The umpires are back out in the middle and so are the players of England. Skipper, Rohit Sharma and Yashasvi Jaiswal are the usual openers for India. James Anderson will start proceedings with the ball here.
... SECOND INNINGS ...

Despite the valiant efforts of Zak Crawley, whose resilient innings provided a glimmer of hope for the English side, the rest of the batting order succumbed to the relentless pressure exerted by the Indian bowlers. As wickets continued to tumble, England found themselves bowled out for a modest total of 218 runs, with the Indian bowlers asserting their dominance and stamping their authority on the proceedings. Now its India to bat on a wicket that is still a good one for the batters. Stay tuned as the Indian innings starts soon.

Kuldeep Yadav's mesmerizing spell of spin bowling proved to be the turning point of the innings, as he dismantled the top order with surgical precision. With a brilliant display of guile and control, Yadav claimed a sensational five-wicket haul, decimating the English batting lineup and leaving them reeling at 113 for 3. Complementing Yadav's brilliance was the seasoned campaigner Ravichandran Ashwin, who showcased his class and experience on his 100th Test match appearance. Ashwin's artistry with the ball was on full display as he accounted for four vital wickets, further denting England's hopes of posting a substantial total.

With that, the first innings unfolded with a symphony of drama and skill, showcasing the fierce contest between bat and ball. England, having won the toss and elected to bat, scored 218 runs in the first innings. The early exchanges saw the English openers navigate the initial overs with caution, weathering the storm of the Indian pace attack. However, as the session progressed, the Indian bowlers, led by the masterful Kuldeep Yadav, seized control of the proceedings.

OUT! CAUGHT! Oh, straight to the man! Ravichandran Ashwin drags this one down on off stump, James Anderson takes on the pull and nails it as well. The ball though is hit flat and hard and goes straight to a shortish mid-wicket where Devdutt Padikkal takes a good sharp catch to his left. Ashwin ends with a four-fer in the first innings of his 100th game and England are bundled out for 218 runs.

Unfortunate but Foakes has to walk back.

Commentary.Commentary: We are back after TEA and the Players and the Umpires take the field to start the Final Session on Day 1. England struggling on Day 1 after winning the toss and is 194/8 with Ben Foakes and Shoaib Bashir at the crease. Ravichandran Ashwin to start the attack after TEA. Let's Play!
... DAY 1, THIRD SESSION ...

India on the other hand will be very pleased to have England eight down within two sessions on Day 1 on a wicket that looks pretty good for batting. It was the Kuldeep Yadav-show before the Lunch interval and even after the interval as he bowled a prolonged spell and got the first four wickets. Ravindra Jadeja them joined in and got rid of Joe Root after which Kuldeep made it a fifer and Ravichandran Ashwin came back in late in the session to get a couple of quick wickets in the same over. India will be looking to bundle out England quickly after the interval and keep them around the 200-run mark and will also look to make quick runs in the final session. Do join us in about 15 minutes' time to find out how Day 1 ends.

SESSION SUMMARY - 29.3 overs, 94 runs and 6 wickets! What a session we have just witnessed! England will still be shell-shocked with that shocking effort and India will be absolutely delighted with how the spinners bowled in the post-Lunch session. England came into the session being 100 for 2 and took a bit of a sedate approach against the spinners. Zak Crawley who was playing freely, got a bit bogged down and Joe Root was also going slowly at the other end. Soon enough, Crawley got out after which Jonny Bairstow walked in and breathed new life into the innings. However, he too got out and that triggered the batting collapse as the likes of Ben Stokes, Tom Hartley and Mark Wood walked back in quick succession. England went from being 175/3 to 184/8 after which Ben Foakes and Shoaib Bashir have somehow managed to keep their wickets intact.
Flights the ball up on the off stump line. Shoaib Bashir knocks it off the front foot and the Umpires call for TEA.

... DAY 1, SECOND SESSION ...

For India, the first session yielded mixed fortunes as their fast bowlers launched a relentless assault on the English batting lineup. Despite their accuracy and probing lines, luck eluded the Indian camp, with edges finding sanctuary in no man's land, allowing the English openers to survive the early onslaught. Yet, buoyed by Kuldeep Yadav's breakthroughs, India retreated to the sanctity of the dressing room with heads held high, brimming with determination to regroup and mount a spirited fightback in the subsequent sessions. As the players replenish their energies during the lunch break, the air is thick with anticipation. England, buoyed by Crawley's heroics, seeks to capitalize on their solid start and amass a formidable total, while India, spurred on by Kuldeep's exploits, endeavors to wrest control of the match and assert their dominance. Join us back for the Second Session at 12.10 pm IST (6.40 am GMT).

The stage set for a battle of epic proportions as England's openers took guard against the probing deliveries of the Indian fast bowlers. Despite an initial onslaught from the Indian pacers, Ben Duckett fell victim to the crafty spin of Kuldeep Yadav, followed by the departure of Ollie Pope, whose wicket fell just moments before the lunch interval, courtesy of a sublime delivery from the Indian bowlers. However, amidst the ebb and flow of the contest, one man stood tall amidst the ruins, his blade a symphony of precision and power. Zak Crawley, batting on 61 runs and steering the English innings towards stability. Zak Crawley will be a huge factor for England if they want to put up a good first-innings total on a wicket that looks really good for the batters. It will be Zak Crawley joined by Joe Root when we come after Lunch.

SESSION SUMMARY- 25.3 Overs, 100 Runs, 2 Wickets. With that late wicket of Ollie Pope, the umpires signal the end of the enthralling first session on Day 1 with the unmistakable call for LUNCH. The stage is set, the battle lines drawn, as England, after winning the toss and opting to bat first, have notched up a commendable total of 100 runs for the loss of two wickets, setting the tone for what promises to be a riveting encounter.

OUT! STUMPED! A sensational piece of bowling and the keeper called it beforehand as well. Kuldeep Yadav bowls this one flat and outside off stump and drags the length back quite a fair bit. Ollie Pope comes a long way down the track looking to flick it leg side but the ball goes the other way and ends up walking past it. The keeper, Dhruv Jurel who called it before this ball that the batter will come forward, gets his wish and whips off the bails. England lose their second wicket right on the stroke of Lunch.

Commentary.Commentary: Drinks break! A fascinating first hour of play on Day 1 and somehow, the English openers have survived the new ball. Jasprit Bumrah and Mohammed Siraj bowled pretty well for the first 8-10 overs and Bumrah in particular bowled a couple of magical deliveries but couldn't find the breakthrough. Zak Crawley has looked good and even though Ben Duckett has looked tentative, he has managed to stay on the crease and England will now look to consolidate with spin, in all likeliness, ruling the roost in the next hour of play.
Hits the length hard on top of the off stump line. Ben Duckett gets back on the crease and knocks it off to end the first hour of play in this Test Match.

Commentary.Commentary: We are almost ready to go! The Indian team is already out in the middle and Ravichandran Ashwin gets a guard of honor from his teammates as he takes the field. The umpires are also out in the middle and the Indian players now take their places on the field. Zak Crawley and Ben Duckett will open the innings for England. Jasprit Bumrah has the new ball in hand and is raring to go. Three slips and a gully in place. Let's go...

The live visuals from the ground show Ravichandran Ashwin being felicitated in front of the whole team and his family as coach Rahul Dravid speaks a few words and hands over that 100th Test cap. A few minutes earlier, we also saw Jonny Bairstow being felicitated by the England coaching staff with the team in a huddle and his family present as well. A memorable occasion for both players who will be itching to do well in this milestone Test. Stick around as the first ball isn't far away now.

Rohit Sharma, the skipper of India says that they would have batted as well on this wicket. Adds that any Test match for the country is always a very important match and they will look to play well and finish the series on a high. Says that the wicket looks really good and hard and they expect some good bounce which they have not seen much in the series. Talks about Ashwin’s 100th Test Match and says that he is a champion bowler and they will expect him to come out and give his best as always. Ends by saying that there are 2 changes in the side for them today, Jasprit comes in for Akash and Devdutt makes his Test Debut.

Ben Stokes, the captain of England, says that they will bat first and the overhead conditions and everything looks good. Adds that the experiences a few players have had as individuals is something to keep and eye on and would want to end with a win. Mentions that it is about pride when you play for the country and goes on to appreciate the commitment and desire to play that Jonny Bairstow has displayed to play his 100th Test. Confirms that they have one change with Mark Wood coming in for Ollie Robinson.

India (Playing XI) - Yashasvi Jaiswal, Rohit Sharma (C), Shubman Gill, Devdutt Padikkal (In for Rajat Patidar), Ravindra Jadeja, Sarfaraz Khan, Dhruv Jurel (WK), Ravichandran Ashwin, Kuldeep Yadav, Mohammed Siraj, Jasprit Bumrah (In for Akash Deep).

England (Playing XI) - Zak Crawley, Ben Duckett, Ollie Pope, Joe Root, Jonny Bairstow, Ben Stokes (C), Ben Foakes (WK), Tom Hartley, Mark Wood (In place of Ollie Robinson), James Anderson, Shoaib Bashir.
TOSS - England have won the Toss and elected to BAT first.

While a couple of stalwarts, one on each side are playing their 100th Test match in the form of Ravichandran Ashwin and Jonny Bairstow, Devdutt Padikkal gets his Test cap from Ravichandran Ashwin and will be the 5th debutant from India in this series.

PITCH REPORT - Sanjay Manjrekar is pitchside. He says that it is going to be a nice clear day and the outfield looks fantastic as well. Nick Knight joins him and says that the pitch looks like a belter and the ground is smallish as well and one would love to bat first. Reckons the carry will be good and there might be some movement for the seamers early on.

As the teams unveil their battle plans, England makes a strategic maneuver, opting to bolster their pace attack by including Mark Wood in place of Ollie Robinson, while retaining the services of spinners Shoaib Bashir and Tom Hartley. Meanwhile, India maintains an aura of mystery surrounding their Playing XI, keeping pundits and fans alike guessing. Will the hosts opt for three seamers to exploit the conditions, or will they maintain their faith in the spin department? The debut dilemma persists as well, with the tantalizing prospect of Devdutt Padikkal making his maiden appearance for India looming large on the horizon. In the crucible of competition, where destinies are forged and legends are born, every delivery carries the weight of expectation, every stroke resonates with the echoes of glory. As the HPCA Stadium in Dharamsala braces itself for the ultimate spectacle of cricketing prowess, the stage is set for a battle royale that transcends boundaries and captivates the imagination of millions. So, fasten your seatbelts and brace yourselves for a cricketing extravaganza that promises to redefine the very essence of sporting excellence. Stay tuned for Toss and Line up updates.

India, riding high on the wings of triumph, seeks to cap off their dominance with a resounding 4-1 finish, thereby etching their name in the annals of cricketing glory. Spearheading their charge is the dynamic Yashasvi Jaiswal, whose stellar performances have illuminated the series thus far, emerging as the leading run-scorer for the Indian contingent. With the spotlight firmly trained upon him, Jaiswal stands poised to deliver yet another masterclass, as he leads India's quest for cricketing immortality.  Amidst the frosty backdrop, the stage is set for a momentous milestone as India's Ravichandran Ashwin and England's Jonny Bairstow prepare to etch their names in the annals of cricketing history by featuring in their 100th Test match for their respective countries. A poignant coincidence binds the two stalwarts, as both Ashwin and Bairstow had made their debuts against West Indies, setting the stage for a captivating narrative of cricketing excellence and enduring legacy. Yet, amidst the celebrations and milestones, the stakes loom large for the Indian contingent, with the World Test Championship points table casting a shadow of significance over the proceedings. A resounding 4-1 finish for India could potentially bolster their position at the summit of the table, further solidifying their claim to cricketing supremacy on the global stage.

In the breathtaking expanse of the Himalayan foothills, amidst the pristine beauty of Dharamsala, the stage is set for the grand finale of an enthralling cricketing saga. The 5th and Final Test match between cricketing powerhouses India and England is poised to commence at the illustrious HPCA Stadium, Dharamsala. With the series already tilted in favor of the home team, India, who have clinched victory in three out of four encounters, the anticipation reaches a fever pitch as both teams vie for supremacy in this ultimate showdown. As the action resumes after a 10-day hiatus, the players brace themselves for the daunting challenge that lies ahead, traversing through the bone-chilling environs of Dharamsala. In a testament to the unforgiving nature of the conditions, even the stoutest of garments may prove inadequate against the icy grip of the cold, with temperatures plummeting to a frigid 1 degree Celsius, offering a stern test of endurance and resilience to both teams.
... MATCH DAY ...

We are back for England's second innings! The umpires are back out in the middle and so are the players of India. Zak Crawley and Ben Duckett come out to open the innings for England as they look to somehow wipe off a deficit of 259 runs. Jasprit Bumrah will take the new ball and he is raring to go. Also, there's no Rohit Sharma on the field not quite sure why and Bumrah will be the acting skipper for now. Let's play...
... THIRD INNINGS ...

Indi only added 4 runs to their overnight score but will be pretty content as Kuldeep Yadav and Jasprit Bumrah put on a 49-run stand for the 10th wicket which took the lead to a mammoth 259 runs. The top five batters all got to at least a fifty and there were a couple of hundreds as well as Rohit Sharma and Shubman Gill brought up the three-figure mark. Kuldeep, yet again put on a strong showing with the bat and his stellar performances with the ball seem to be rubbing off on his batting as well. They will now look to attack from the off and get early wickets and try to set up an innings win. The pitch though looks pretty good for batting still and it is all about the execution of the English batters and their temperament. Join us in a few minutes time as England's second innings is up next.

Right then, just over 4 overs needed for England to get the two remaining wickets and they will be mightily relieved. A couple of milestones were achieved in the process as well as James Anderson became the third bowler in history to take 700 Test wickets when he nicked off Kuldeep Yadav and now with that stumping, Shoaib Bashir picks up a stellar five-wicket haul where he was made to toil but he never gave up and got his dues. Anderson, rightly, gets a huge round of applause from his teammates and the crowd while walking back to the pavilion but it is all about the English top order and what they can do to counter the Indian attack.

The Umpire refers it to the Third Umpire and it looks really close for Jasprit Bumrah as his back foot is just on the line with nothing behind it. The Big screen shows OUT and India are bowled out for 477.

Commentary.Commentary: All set now for Day 3 to get underway! The umpires are out in the middle and the players of England have taken their places on the field. Kuldeep Yadav and Jasprit Bumrah are ready to resume their overnight stay at the crease for India. It will be the off-spin of Shoaib Bashir to get things underway with the ball on Day 3. Let's play...

However, England, despite facing an uphill battle, will be eager to stage a comeback and claw their way back into contention. With the experience of Ben Stokes leading the charge, the visitors will seek to make inroads into the Indian batting lineup and restrict their lead to a manageable margin. Shoaib Bashir is the pick of the bowlers for England as he picked up 4 wickets yesterday and will be eyeing his second Five Wicket Haul in this series. The morning session promises to be a riveting affair, with India's tailenders Jasprit Bumrah and Kuldeep Yadav resuming their partnership, intent on adding valuable runs to India's total. As the battle between bat and ball unfolds under the azure skies, the outcome of the match looks to be going India's way at the moment. Can England turn things around? Let's find out as we are moments away from the start of Day 3 of this Test Match.

On Day 2, Rohit Sharma and Shubman Gill mesmerized the crowd with their scintillating centuries, propelling India to a commanding position with a substantial first-innings lead. Buoyed by their stellar performances, India's top order showcased their prowess with the bat, leaving the visitors reeling and firmly in control of the match. The debutant Devdutt Padikkal, along with Sarfaraz Khan and Yashasvi Jaiswal crossed the 50-run mark each and batted really well against the English bowlers. Kuldeep Yadav and Jasprit Bumrah are the not-out batters for India when they walk out to bat today. India already sits on a lead of 255 runs and making a comeback in this game is getting tougher and tougher for England. The more this batting pair plays for India, the more frustrating it is going to get for the English players.

As the sun peeks over the horizon, casting a golden glow upon the verdant expanse of the cricketing arena, anticipation mounts for another exhilarating day of Test cricket at Dharamshala. With memories of Day 2 still fresh in the minds of players and spectators alike, the stage is set for a day of enthralling cricketing action as India prepares to resume their innings at 473/8 standing on a first-innings lead of 255 runs against England in the fifth and final Test Match.
... DAY 3, FIRST SESSION ...

Right then, India have a big lead of 255 runs and aren't quite done yet and will look to take it beyond 300 runs. Yet again, Ben Stokes needs to channelize every ounce of positive radiation within the camp to show the same gut which they showed in the first Test, but with every passing game, the task keeps getting tougher and tougher as it does seem as if the first Test never happened. Nevertheless, first job, England need to get those remaining two wickets as quickly as possible and then, try and bat, bat and bat. A lot of questions to be answered and Day 3 is generally the moving day and this one doesn't seem any different. Day 3 will commence on Saturday at 9.30 am IST (4 am GMT) but you can join us sooner for the build-up as well.

The centurion, Shubman Gill is down for a quick chat. Gill says that it was his father’s dream that he play for the country and he hopes that his father is proud of him. Talks about his shot against James Anderson that went for a maximum, and he says that it felt good playing that shot. Says that it's always good to play on this wicket and accepts that he could have got a big score but missed out.

The final session on Day 2 started with two young Indian batters set on the crease but Sarfaraz Khan was a bit too eager and got out on the very first ball after Tea. Devdutt Padikkal went on to score his maiden 50 in his maiden Test innings and he too got out soon after. Shoaib Bashir bowled a lovely spell and kept on chipping away and eventually, he found some success. Dhruv Jurel and Ravindra Jadeja tried to stitch together a partnership but weren't able to play freely and eventually, Jurel got out playing a false shot and Jadeja soon followed suit. Tom Hartley got both of those wickets and England seemed to be in control. However, Kuldeep Yadav, high on a fifer and a resilient Jasprit Bumrah didn't give their wickets away and have put on an unbeaten stand of 45 runs and will look to muster up quick runs at the start of Day 3.

Another engrossing day of Test cricket that provided a lot of entertainment but at the end of it all, yet again, it is India who have a firm grip on the game. England had their moments right after the Lunch interval and then after the Tea interval and even midway through the final session, but they haven't been able to be lethal enough and have ended up conceding a lead of 255 runs.
Hits the good length on top of the off stump line and Kuldeep Yadav takes out the front foot and knocks the ball straight top point to end the Day 2 of the Test Match.

Commentary.Commentary: DRINKS! Kuldeep Yadav walks out to bat for India as Ravindra Jadeja walks out and the Umpires call for DRINKS for the last time today. One hour of play left for the day. Will England get the remaining 3 wickets of India and start their batting? Or will India survive tonight and come back fresh tomorrow? Let's find out in the final hour or so of play coming.

OUT! LBW! A huge appeal and the finger does go up. Tom Hartley comes from over the stumps and tosses it up on a good length around off and middle and gets the ball to turn back in. The ball also skids on and Ravindra Jadeja gets caught on the back foot. Jadeja ends up playing all over it and gets pinged on the pads. Jadeja does review it and there's nothing on UltraEdge. Ball Tracking comes up with three reds and Jadeja is a goner as well. England will now have their tails up.

Commentary.Commentary: All in readiness for the post-Tea session to begin! The umpires are back out in the middle and so are the players of England. Sarfaraz Khan and Devdutt Padikkal are also set to resume their stay on the crease for India. It will be Shoaib Bashir to bowl after the break.
... DAY 2, SESSION 3 ...

The session began with a couple of masters of the game bowling a wonderful spell as England's skipper Ben Stokes got a wicket off the very first ball that he bowled on this tour. It was a beauty as well and Rohit Sharma had to walk back right away his century. This galvanized James Anderson at the other end and he conjured up a stellar delivery of his own in the next over and sent Shubman Gill packing as well. Since then though, the pair of Devdutt Padikkal and Sarfaraz Khan has done immaculately well for the hosts and have added 97 runs. Padikkal seemed a bit edgy but soon started to time the ball well and Khan took his time before unleashing a barrage of boundaries and got to a half-century. The stage is nicely set for India to get a really massive first-innings lead but can England do what they did right after Lunch and get rid of the set-batters? Join us in a few minutes to find out in the final session of Day 2.

SESSION SUMMARY - 24 overs, 112 runs and 2 wickets! A fascinating session of Test cricket comes to an end and it was a session that promised a lot for England but soon enough, they were put on the back foot yet again. It could have been a session that got things back in the balance but two young Indian batters have made sure that the hosts have the upper hand and have taken the lead to 158 runs already.

... DAY 2, SECOND SESSION ...

As the players retreat to the sanctity of the dressing rooms for the interval, the stage is set for a riveting second session, where fortunes will be decided and destinies forged amidst the crucible of competition. With India firmly in the driver's seat, the onus is on England to regroup, reassess their strategies, and mount a spirited fightback to wrest control of the match from their formidable opponents. Will this Test match go one way? Or will England find a way to stage a comeback from here? The answers lie in the Second Session coming up fight after LUNCH. Join us at 12.10 pm IST (6.40 am GMT) for the start of the Second Session.

While the Indian batters have flourished under the azure skies of Dharamsala, the English bowlers toiled tirelessly, their efforts hampered by a placid surface that offered little assistance. Despite their perseverance, the Indian batters remained resolute, showcasing their class and skill with a breathtaking array of strokes that left the crowd enraptured and the English camp reeling. As the session drew to a close, the English side found themselves facing an uphill battle, with the prospect of a substantial first-innings lead looming ominously on the horizon if they fail to stem the flow of runs and find a way to get a few quick wickets soon.

SESSION SUMMARY - 30 Overs, 129 Runs, 0 Wickets. As the umpires signal the conclusion of the First Session on Day 2, the scene is set for an enthralling day of Test cricket, with India firmly in control of proceedings. Riding high on a wave of dominance, India has asserted their authority without losing a wicket in the session, amassing a formidable total of 264 runs for the loss of just one wicket, seizing a commanding lead of 46 runs. Spearheading the Indian charge are the dynamic duo of Rohit Sharma, the indomitable Indian skipper, and the talented Shubman Gill. Sharma, continuing his imperious form, etched his name into the annals of cricketing history with yet another century, his blade a symphony of elegance and power as he remains unbeaten on 102. Gill, equally resplendent, showcased his prodigious talent with a scintillating century of his own, his strokeplay a testament to his burgeoning prowess at the crease, with the duo stitching together a formidable partnership of 160 runs.

Commentary.Commentary: We are all set for Day 2 to begin! The two umpires are already out in the middle and so are the players of England. Skipper, Rohit Sharma and Shubman Gill are set to resume their overnight stay at the crease. It will be spin to start the proceedings with the ball as Shoaib Bashir has been handed the ball.

As the stage is set for another day of riveting cricketing action, the narrative unfolds with tantalizing possibilities, offering a canvas upon which heroes will rise, and legends will be forged. With the fate of the match hanging in the balance, Day 2 promises to be a spectacle of cricketing brilliance, where fortunes will be decided and destinies entwined in the crucible of competition. India will start the Day at 135/1 with Rohit Sharma and Shubman Gill at the crease for them. Dont go anywhere as we bring you Day 2 of this 5th Test Match between India and England. Stay tuned.

For England, the dawn of Day 2 heralds a moment of reckoning, as they endeavor to recalibrate their strategies and mount a spirited fightback in the face of adversity. With the memories of Day 1 serving as a stark reminder of their missed opportunities and unfulfilled potential, England must summon all their resolve and resilience to claw their way back into contention and salvage their pride in the final Test of the series.

As the sun begins its ascent above the majestic peaks surrounding the picturesque Dharamsala, anticipation brews in the air, heralding the dawn of a new day of cricketing action at the hallowed grounds of the match. With the echoes of the pulsating contest from Day 1 still reverberating through the stadium, all eyes turn towards the Indian skipper, Rohit Sharma, and his steadfast partner, Shubman Gill, as they prepare to resume their innings and build upon the solid foundation laid on the previous day. India now trail by 83 runs and stand on 135/1. Sharma, buoyed by his commanding presence at the crease, will seek to continue his prolific form, while Gill will be eager to capitalize on his promising start and convert it into a substantial contribution for the team.
... DAY 2, FIRST SESSION ...

Right then, India trail England by just 83 runs and they have as many as 9 wickets in hand. With plenty of batting to come, the hosts will look to bat out Day 2 and take a big first-innings lead but England will come at them hard and with not much to lose, we might just see things happening from the visitors' side. Join us on Friday, 8 March for a fascinating Day 2 of this 5th Test which will commence at 9.30 am IST (4 am GMT). You can tune in to the build-up a lot sooner though. Cheers!

England will look back on this day and will be reminded of the entire series as Day 1 summed up their tour perfectly. They have got themselves into promising and even dominating positions but have just not been able to take advantage. After being 100/2, they could only manage to put on 218 runs and got bundled out in just over two sessions on Day 1. With the ball in hand soon after, the pacers couldn't do much damage early on and were dealt with by the Indian openers. The spinners bowled decently well and created some doubt in the minds of the batters but went for runs too. Shoaib Bashir got hammered away but did come back strongly and got rid of the dangerman Yashasvi Jaiswal but still, England are well behind the eight-ball here.

SESSION SUMMARY - 32.4 overs, 159 runs and 3 wickets! A commanding session from India to end Day 1 of this fifth and final Test in Dharamsala. Things moved quickly after Lunch as England lost wickets in a heap and were bowled out a few overs after the Tea interval. Since then though, the Indian openers dominated and have put the hosts in a very good position going into Day 2. Yashasvi Jaiswal continued his fine form as he racked up 700 runs in the series before nothing up yet another 50 but he did lose his wicket trying to be too aggressive. Skipper, Rohit Sharma wasn't quite in full flow at the other end but put the bad balls away and got settled as well. He too brought up a half century as India ended the day with 9 wickets intact with Rohit and Shubman Gill both well-set.

Commentary.Commentary: Right then, a series that began on 25th January has finally reached its conclusion on the 9th Match and what a five-match series this has turned out to be. Rohit Sharma receives the series-win trophy and walks to the podium where he hands it to the youngsters and they revel in the joy and pose for a team photograph, amazing scenes. We rarely see five Test matches being played but that's what made this one very engrossing and after Ollie Pope led England to a remarkable victory in Hyderabad in the 1st Test, things quickly got galvanized. India lost a few key players and handed out as many as five debuts throughout the series and all of them contributed to the comeback. Rohit Sharma led the side well and there were some memorable individual performances as India rampaged back to a 4-1 win. Both teams will be now away from international cricket for a while and most players will gear up for the upcoming Indian T20 League. We hope you enjoyed our coverage and until next time, take care and goodbye!

The Indian skipper, Rohit Sharma starts by saying that a lot of things pleased him in this Test and they did a lot of things right throughout the match. Adds that at some stage people are going to go and new guys are going to come in and even though the new guys are short in experience, they played well and his job was to make them understand the situation better and they were able to perform under pressure. Mentions that when you win a series like this, you talk about runs on the board but it is equally important to take 20 wickets in a Test match and they came close in the first game after which they were able to achieve that feat and the bowlers did a fine job. On Kuldeep Yadav, he says that it was a long conversation every now and then with him and has the potential to be a regular match-winner and he has got something about him that everyone needs to accept and be happy about and the way he has bounced back after the injury is commendable. On Yashasvi Jaiswal, he says that he has a long way to go and has started off brilliantly and we saw throughout the series that he wants to put bowlers under pressure from the word go and that is something they want to encourage and there will be challenges ahead but he has come a long way already.

Yashasvi Jaiswal is the Player of the Series for scoring more than 700 runs in the five Test matches including a couple of double hundreds as well. Jaiswal says that he really enjoyed it and the series gives him a lot of experience. On the amount of sixes he hit, he adds that he was just thinking to play his shots and if he felt like he wanted to take the bowler down, he went for it. Mentions that he is trying to play one match at a time and help his team in any way possible.

Kuldeep Yadav is the Player of the Match for his stellar performance. Kuldeep says that he reckons this is the best he has bowled and it is all due to the hard work he put in over the last couple of years. Adds that his best performance came in Ranchi and he enjoyed bowling on it and reckons that he liked the wicket of Ben Stokes in Ranchi. Adds that he is just focusing on the length and is trying to bowl on a good length and it is helping a lot not to think about what the batter is looking to go. Ends by saying that the credit goes to the batting coach who helped him a lot and even in the mental aspect.

Ben Stokes, the captain of England says that the series has come to an end and they have a lot of positives to take back as they have a lot of cricket coming up against Pakistan and Australia. He further adds that the players are all professionals and are performing at the highest level, for new people it is not very easy to come out and express themselves straight away and he gives credit to all the debutants who managed to leave an impact on the stage. He finally talks about the 700th wicket of James Anderson and says that he is someone every kid who wants to be a fast bowler should look up to and he is still brilliant to watch.
The Presentation ceremony...

The Indian head coach, Rahul Dravid now comes up for a chat as well. Dravid says that he is really proud and to go behind in the 1st Test was a bit disappointing but credit to the boys for bouncing back. Adds that it was nice to see the boys fight back after being pegged down on various occasions and gives credit to the support staff as well. Reckons that it can be tough when you lose players of such high stature and adds the amount of talent there is in India and one could see that throughout the series. Gives credit to the selectors as well as they did a fine job of picking the team. Says that there were many standout performances and it is hard to pick one but Ravichandran Ashwin's effort to come back after a difficult 24 hours shows what this team is made of.

The star of the moment in his 100th Test match, Ravichandran Ashwin is down for a chat. Ashwin says that he is feeling extremely happy to have bowled well in his 100th Test Match. Adds on by saying that in a country like India, the wickets from city to city are very different and the bowlers adjust according to the wicket on offer. He mentions that he extremely enjoyed bowling on this wicket even though he went for a few hits. He talks about taking criticism well and he says that he works hard to become better every match. Ends by saying that there are a lot of batters who play spinner really well and with all the videos going around it is very important to stay on top of that as it requires you to outsmart yourself at times to do something that is never done before and he looks to keep working on his bowling and keep picking wickets for the country.

India will be absolutely thrilled with that victory and with how the series panned out after that shocking loss in the first Test in Hyderabad that seems to have happened ages ago it seems. It was a near-perfect performance as all their top five batters got runs, with three fifties and two centuries and then spin ruled the roost in both innings. Kuldeep Yadav, on a high from the last game, picked up another five-wicket haul as Ravichandran Ashwin racked up 4 wickets in his 100th Test and then went on to pick up a fifer himself in the second innings to make it 9 wickets in the game. Kuldeep bowled well in the second innings as well and Jasprit Bumrah who captained the side on the field in the second innings bowled a lovely spell in the middle to knock over a couple of wickets. All in all, it was a stellar performance and the hosts will be very proud of it.

England had a poor showing with the bat in the first innings after opting to bat first on a pitch that seemed pristine for batting and that's where they lost the game, on Day 1 itself. They failed to make inroads with the ball as well and thanks to some real persistence from Shoaib Bashir, they managed to finally bundle out the opposition having conceded a lead of 259 runs. With the pitch still good for batting, the English openers got out cheaply and a struggling Ollie Pope soon followed suit. This put pressure on the middle order and there was a counter-punch from Joe Root and Jonny Bairstow but that didn't last long either. Root held up one end and played some quality shots as well but the wickets kept tumbling on the other end and the skipper, Ben Stokes got out on the stroke of Lunch. Root stitched a steady stand with Bashir down the order and looked all set for a fighting ton but in the end, he went for a big shot and was the last man to be dismissed.

INDIA WIN THE SERIES 4-1! What a dominating performance this has been in Dharamshala from the hosts as they have wrapped up proceedings inside three days and have sealed the 5th and final Test match by an innings and 64 runs, a huge margin of victory. England were already five down when the players went into the Lunch break and after an astute fightback from Joe Root, they have folded before Tea and will be truly disappointed as they reflect on what could have been if they had just applied themselves better when the opportunities were presented to them.

OUT! CAUGHT! India finish the match within 3 days and lift the series 4-1! Kuldeep Yadav flights the ball up on the off stump line and Joe Root dances down the track and launches the ball flat and straight to Jasprit Bumrah at long on, who takes a reverse cup and punches the air with joy.

... DAY 3, SECOND SESSION ...

With just five wickets needed to secure victory and seal the series with a resounding 4-1 triumph, India stands on the cusp of a historic achievement. As the teams retreat to the sanctity of the dressing rooms for the lunch break, anticipation mounts for the impending conclusion of the series. Will the coming Second Session be the last of the series? The answer lies in the unfolding drama of the coming session. Let us await with bated breath as the thrilling saga of the series reaches its climax.

Day 3 began with India losing their final two wickets in the early exchanges, with James Anderson reaching the monumental milestone of 700 Test wickets. England commenced their second innings trailing by 255 runs, only to face immediate setbacks as their top order crumbled under the relentless pressure exerted by Ravichandran Ashwin. Ashwin's mastery with the ball was on full display as he claimed four vital wickets, dismantling the English batting lineup with precision and guile. Despite a brief resistance from Jonny Bairstow and Joe Root, England found themselves facing an uphill battle as India tightened their grip on the match.

As the morning sun ascends to its zenith, casting a radiant glow upon the cricketing arena, the curtains fall on a gripping first session of Day 3, with India firmly in the driver's seat, having seized control of the match. India's dominance was evident as they claimed five crucial English wickets for a mere 103 runs in a display of relentless bowling prowess. The session culminated in the dismissal of England's skipper, Ben Stokes, on the penultimate ball before the lunch interval, leaving the visitors reeling and India poised for victory.
